Opportunity:
roblem to solve: Contract review/redlining is slow, inconsistent, and error-prone (version drift, undefined terms, broken cross-references), delaying deals and increasing risk.

Primary users: In-house legal, procurement, sales/RevOps, founders/ops at SMBs, and outside counsel needing quick turnarounds.

Jobs-to-be-done:

Compare two drafts and produce clean redlines;

Auto-categorize clauses and surface gaps;

Check defined-term consistency and cross-references;

Assess risk and flag negotiation items;

Generate executive/board-friendly summaries;

Adjust commentary by governing law (e.g., U.S., England & Wales).

Why this solution: Purpose-built outputs (markup [~del~]/[+add+], clause labels, risk notes, negotiation flags) map directly to legal workflows, unlike generic chat outputs.

Differentiators: Structured templates (Quick Summary, Detailed Comparison, Negotiation Notes, Executive Summary), neutrality (no legal advice), automatic party anonymization, jurisdiction-aware commentary.

Expected impact (hypotheses): Faster cycle time to signature, fewer escalations to senior counsel, higher consistency across drafts, clearer negotiation posture, and reduced oversight mistakes.
